    72	### Why tracking 7.x specifically cost so much time
    73	
    74	1. **A major-version bump is not a point upgrade.** Going 6.18 → 7.0 changed
    75	   in-kernel APIs the out-of-tree NPU driver depends on. Examples we had to
    76	   fix by hand on the new tree: `pm_runtime_put` became `void` (broke the
    77	   driver's error-checking assignments), `IRQF_ONESHOT` on a non-threaded
    78	   IRQ started throwing a probe-time `WARN`, and the ACPI override path
    79	   needed re-prepending. Each was a silent break discovered only by building
    80	   and booting on metal.
    81	
    82	2. **The NPU module is out-of-tree and must be rebuilt per kernel.** It
    83	   isn't in the official patch set, so every kernel rev = recompile the
    84	   `armchina_npu.ko` against the exact new headers/vermagic, re-sign,
    85	   re-prepend the ACPI SSDT, re-stage the initrd. On the new `main` kernel
    86	   this meant standing up a **DKMS-style rebuild** because the prebuilt
    87	   module no longer matched.
    88	
    89	3. **Cross-compilation kept failing.** The cross toolchain choked on the
    90	   7.x tree (`Makefile:2110 Error 2`), so we **abandoned cross-compile and
    91	   built natively on the Sky1 board itself**, inside a Podman container we
    92	   then had to back up as a quadlet so a re-image wouldn't lose the build
    93	   environment. That pivot was necessary but cost days.
    94	
    95	4. **Two (really three) kernels in parallel.** To never ship a regression,
   150	fbdev‑restore fix to survive the desktop. This is the area the new CIX release
   151	most improves (proper `linlondp` fbdev/KMS ops), which is why we're rebasing.
