- `NEXT_CMDLINE_BASE` at [line 251](/home/jasonperlow/cix-installer-build/cix-installer/post-install/70-bootloader.sh:251) has no display blacklist, so it exercises full edge KMS/display.
- `NEXT_CMDLINE_BASE` also omits `efi=noruntime`, while `LTS_CMDLINE_BASE` includes it at [line 229](/home/jasonperlow/cix-installer-build/cix-installer/post-install/70-bootloader.sh:229). The comment rationale for omitting it was systemd-boot boot counting at [lines 210-218](/home/jasonperlow/cix-installer-build/cix-installer/post-install/70-bootloader.sh:210), but this installer now uses rEFInd with `use_nvram false` at [line 518](/home/jasonperlow/cix-installer-build/cix-installer/post-install/70-bootloader.sh:518), so that rationale is stale.
- Repo docs say LTS is the production default with all drivers working: [assets/rescue/AGENTS.md](/home/jasonperlow/cix-installer-build/cix-installer/assets/rescue/AGENTS.md:35), [docs/DRIVER_FIDELITY_7012.md](/home/jasonperlow/cix-installer-build/cix-installer/docs/DRIVER_FIDELITY_7012.md:5).
- Plymouth is not the root cause: [60-plymouth.sh](/home/jasonperlow/cix-installer-build/cix-installer/post-install/60-plymouth.sh:105) unmarks `plymouth-quit`/`plymouth-quit-wait`, and only rebuilds initrds afterward.
- Network config is not a plausible standalone cause of “Ethernet never comes up”: [33-network.sh](/home/jasonperlow/cix-installer-build/cix-installer/post-install/33-network.sh:140) enables `NetworkManager-wait-online`, but its own comment says this is bounded and does not block login/ssh at [lines 137-139](/home/jasonperlow/cix-installer-build/cix-installer/post-install/33-network.sh:137). If the kernel reaches userspace, NM should be enabled at [line 130](/home/jasonperlow/cix-installer-build/cix-installer/post-install/33-network.sh:130).

Cmdline differences today:
- `ROOT_OPTS`: `root=PARTUUID=$ROOT_PARTUUID rootwait rootfstype=$ROOT_FSTYPE rw`, plus `rootflags=subvol=$ROOT_SUBVOL` for btrfs.
- `LTS_CMDLINE_BASE`: `console=tty0 efi=noruntime acpi=force arm-smmu-v3.disable_bypass=0 audit_backlog_limit=8192 clk_ignore_unused panic=30 module_blacklist=typec_rts5453,rts5453`
- `NEXT_CMDLINE_BASE`: `console=tty0 acpi=force arm-smmu-v3.disable_bypass=0 audit_backlog_limit=8192 clk_ignore_unused panic=30 module_blacklist=typec_rts5453,rts5453`
- Only current LTS/EDGE difference: `efi=noruntime`.
- `SPLASH`: `quiet splash`
- `DEFAULT_TOKEN`: currently `edge` when NEXT exists, else `stable`.

**Minimal Patch**

```diff
diff --git a/post-install/70-bootloader.sh b/post-install/70-bootloader.sh
--- a/post-install/70-bootloader.sh
+++ b/post-install/70-bootloader.sh
@@ -210,15 +210,12 @@
-# LTS keeps efi=noruntime (r74 ship stability; original MS-R1 EFI
-# runtime quirk worked around by disabling it). NEXT drops it because
-# systemd-bless-boot requires EFI runtime variables (LoaderBootCountPath)
-# to mark a successful boot as good — without that, repeated successful
-# NEXT boots burn the +N-M counter to .failed and roll back to LTS.
-# linux-cix-sky1-next 7.0.x has newer EFI handling than the 6.6 fork
-# the noruntime workaround was originally added for; defaulting to
-# runtime-enabled on NEXT lets the auto-rollback semantics actually
-# work as designed.
+# LTS and NEXT both keep efi=noruntime. The MS-R1 firmware runtime-services
+# quirk is still relevant, and rEFInd has no systemd-bless-boot boot counting
+# path to protect here.
@@
-NEXT_CMDLINE_BASE="console=tty0 acpi=force arm-smmu-v3.disable_bypass=0 audit_backlog_limit=8192 clk_ignore_unused panic=30 module_blacklist=typec_rts5453,rts5453"
+NEXT_CMDLINE_BASE="console=tty0 efi=noruntime acpi=force arm-smmu-v3.disable_bypass=0 audit_backlog_limit=8192 clk_ignore_unused panic=30 module_blacklist=typec_rts5453,rts5453"
@@ -427,8 +424,8 @@
-# r130.5 (operator): the rescue partition boots the LTS 6.18 kernel with the
-# same NPU/GPU/VPU/KMS module_blacklist as the rescue.target pin above — a
-# recovery env must be boring/reliable, not exercise edge silicon (the edge
-# kernel's full device probing caused "sloppy device startup").
+# r130.6: the rescue partition boots the LTS 6.18 kernel with the normal LTS
+# cmdline, not the rescue.target KMS/display blacklist. It is a standalone
+# operator environment and must have a usable local console.
@@
-        # RESCUE_CMDLINE_SAFE carries the NPU/GPU/VPU/KMS blacklist (built above
-        # for the rescue.target pin); reuse it here, minus rescue.target/ROOT_OPTS,
-        # so the dedicated rescue rootfs boots quietly to a normal login.
-        RESCUEPART_OPTIONS="root=PARTUUID=$RESCUEPART_PARTUUID rootwait rootfstype=ext4 rw $RESCUE_CMDLINE_SAFE"
-        echo "  rescue-partition ready (PARTUUID=$RESCUEPART_PARTUUID) — adding rEFInd rescuepart entry (LTS + safe blacklist)"
+        RESCUEPART_OPTIONS="root=PARTUUID=$RESCUEPART_PARTUUID rootwait rootfstype=ext4 rw $LTS_CMDLINE_BASE"
+        echo "  rescue-partition ready (PARTUUID=$RESCUEPART_PARTUUID) — adding rEFInd rescuepart entry (LTS + normal display cmdline)"
@@ -501,10 +498,10 @@
-# default_selection matches a substring of the menu-entry title. edge is the
-# default when staged, else stable. rescue is always manual-only.
-if [ "$NEXT_AVAILABLE" = "1" ]; then
-    DEFAULT_TOKEN="edge"
-else
+# default_selection matches a substring of the menu-entry title. MS-R1 fleet
+# default is stable/LTS; edge is a manual beta entry. Rescue is manual-only.
+if [ "$LTS_AVAILABLE" = "1" ]; then
     DEFAULT_TOKEN="stable"
+else
+    DEFAULT_TOKEN="edge"
 fi
@@
-        echo "menuentry \"NCZ-OS 26.6  ·  edge — kernel $KVER_NEXT (NEXT 7.0.x) [DEFAULT/BETA]\" {"
+        echo "menuentry \"NCZ-OS 26.6  ·  edge — kernel $KVER_NEXT (NEXT 7.0.x) [BETA]\" {"
```

Optional doc cleanup to avoid future confusion:

```diff
diff --git a/post-install/72-rescue-partition.sh b/post-install/72-rescue-partition.sh
--- a/post-install/72-rescue-partition.sh
+++ b/post-install/72-rescue-partition.sh
@@ -17,8 +17,8 @@
 # r130.5 (operator): the dedicated rescue partition now ships the LTS 6.18
 # kernel (assets/kernel/stable), NOT the edge 7.0.x. A recovery environment
 # should be boring and reliable; the edge kernel's full accelerator/display
-# probing caused "sloppy device startup". 70-bootloader.sh boots this partition
-# with the same NPU/GPU/VPU/KMS module_blacklist as the rEFInd "rescue" entry.
+# probing caused "sloppy device startup". 70-bootloader.sh boots this partition
+# with the normal LTS cmdline so the local console remains usable.
```

**Recommendation**

Yes: `default_selection` should be LTS/stable on MS-R1. Edge should remain a manual `[BETA]` entry.

Safest edge policy:
- Keep edge present for validation.
- Add `efi=noruntime` back to edge because the rEFInd path no longer benefits from EFI runtime variables.
- Do not make the display-blacklisted edge entry the normal edge entry; it may boot headless, but it is not a useful local-console default on this platform.
- If you want a diagnostic edge-safe mode, add a separate manual “edge headless-safe” entry with the rescue blacklist and no `quiet splash`, intended for SSH/network testing only.
